workflow:

name: Run and build application

on: push # event

jobs:
  build:  // build and test are job names
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest # runs on means what kind of operating system we used
    steps:
      - name: My Code
        uses: actions/checkout@v2  //Download repository code
      - name: Install pacakges
        run: pip install fastapi // install python packages
  test: 
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    needs: build # it means after build job test job will run
    steps:

worklfow contains these :
Events (on)
Jobs
Steps
Actions (uses)
Commands (run)
Environment variables (env)
Secrets
Running tests
Building Docker images

build and test is the job name.
Inside the job, there are multiple steps.
All steps run on the same Ubuntu machine.
GitHub Actions doesn't have fixed "job types." You create jobs based on their purpose.
1. Build Job
Compiles/builds the application.
Purpose:
Build application
Build Docker image
2. Test Job
Runs automated tests.
Purpose:
Check code quality
Catch bugs before deployment
3.Deploy Job:
Deploys the application.
Purpose:
Deploy to AWS, Azure, Kubernetes, etc.
Job Dependencies (needs):
Sometimes you want one job to run only after another succeeds.

Steps:
A step is a single task inside a job.
Each step performs one action, such as:
Checking out code
Installing Python
Installing dependencies
Running tests
Building a Docker image
Types of Steps 
1. uses Step: Uses a pre-built action created by GitHub or the community. This action checks out your repository code.
2.run Step: Executes shell commands.
If any step is failed , next step cannot run .it stops

Actions:
What are Actions in GitHub Actions?
An Action is a reusable piece of code that performs a specific task in a workflow.Instead of writing all the code yourself, you can use an existing action.
You use an action with the uses keyword.
Why do we use Actions?
Without actions, you would have to write many commands manually.
For example, to download your repository code, you could write scripts yourself. Instead, GitHub provides:
ex: - uses: actions/checkout@v4
This action automatically:
Clones your repository
Makes the code available to the workflow
uses is not an action.
uses is a keyword inside a step that tells GitHub Actions to run an action.

Secrets:
Secrets are used to store sensitive information securely.
Examples: Docker Hub username/password
AWS access keys
How to Add a Secret :
GitHub Repository → Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions → New repository secret

Running Tests:
Tests verify that your code works correctly before it is merged or deployed.
For a FastAPI project, you might use pytest.

Building Docker Images:
A Docker image contains:
Application code
Dependencies
Runtime environment

without writing docker file the ci can execute or not:
Yes, CI can execute without a Dockerfile.
A Dockerfile is only needed if your CI pipeline includes a step to build a Docker image.